Primal-Dual Pairs

Symmetric Form of Duality










Primal


Dual




minimize\operatorname{minimize}
𝐜⊤𝐱\bm{c}^\top \bm{x}

maximize\operatorname{maximize}
𝐲⊤𝐛\bm{y}^\top \bm{b}


subject to
𝐀𝐱≥𝐛\bm{Ax} \geq \bm{b}

subject to
𝐲⊤𝐀≤𝐜⊤\bm{y}^\top \bm{A} \leq \bm{c}^\top



𝐱≥𝟎\bm{x} \geq \bm{0}


𝐲≥𝟎\bm{y} \geq \bm{0}




If 𝐀\bm{A} is an m×nm \times n matrix, then 𝐱\bm{x} is an nn-vector, 𝐛\bm{b} is an mm-vector, 𝐜\bm{c} is an nn vector, and 𝐲\bm{y} is an mm-vector.
The vector 𝐱\bm{x} is the variable of the primal program, and 𝐲\bm{y} is he variable of the dual program.







Important


The roles of the primal and the dual can be reversed!

Interchange cost and constraint vectors,
Change minimization to maximization.

Multiplying the objective and the constraints by minus unity, the dual has the structure of the primal.
Its corresponding dual will be equivalent to the original primal.

Primal-Dual Pairs

The dual of any linear program can be found by converting the program to the form of the primal in the previous slide.




Equivalent primal programs




minimize𝐜⊤𝐱,subject to𝐀𝐱=𝐛,𝐱≥𝟎
\begin{align}
\operatorname{minimize} & \bm{c}^\top \bm{x}, \\
\text{subject to} & \bm{Ax} = \bm{b}, \quad \bm{x} \geq \bm{0} 
\end{align}


minimize𝐜⊤𝐱,subject to𝐀𝐱≥𝐛,−𝐀𝐱≥−𝐛,𝐱≥𝟎
\begin{align}
\operatorname{minimize} & \bm{c}^\top \bm{x},  \\
\text{subject to} & \bm{Ax} \geq \bm{b}, \\
& -\bm{Ax} \geq -\bm{b}, \\
& \bm{x} \geq \bm{0} 
\end{align}









Conversion to dual




Partition the dual vector as (𝐮,𝐯)(\bm{u}, \bm{v}), we get
maximize𝐮⊤𝐛−𝐯⊤𝐛,subject to𝐮⊤𝐀−𝐯⊤𝐀≤𝐜⊤,𝐮,𝐯≥𝟎
\begin{align}
\operatorname{maximize} & \bm{u}^\top\bm{b} - \bm{v}^\top\bm{b}, \\
\text{subject to} & \bm{u}^\top\bm{A} - \bm{v}^\top\bm{A} \leq \bm{c}^\top, \\
& \bm{u}, \bm{v} \geq \bm{0} 
\end{align}


Letting 𝐲=𝐮−𝐯\bm{y} = \bm{u} - \bm{v}, this is simplified as
minimize𝐲⊤𝐛,subject to𝐲⊤𝐀≤𝐜⊤.
\begin{align}
\operatorname{minimize} & \bm{y}^\top \bm{b},  \\
\text{subject to} & \bm{y}^\top\bm{A} \leq \bm{c}^\top.
\end{align}







This is the asymmetric form of the duality relation. In this form the dual vector 𝐲\bm{y} is not restricted to be nonnegative.

Example 2 – Dual of the Diet Problem


This problem has the form on the right and hence can be regarded as the primal problem of the symmetric pair.

minimize𝐜⊤𝐱subject to𝐀𝐱≥𝐛,𝐱≥𝟎
\begin{align}
\operatorname{minimize} & \bm{c}^\top \bm{x} \\
\text{subject to} & \bm{Ax} \geq \bm{b}, \quad \bm{x} \geq \bm{0}
\end{align}








Dual Interpretation


Imagine a pharmaceutical company that prodcues in pill form each of the nutrients considered important by the dietitian. The company tries to convince the dietitian to buy pills, and thereby supply the nutrients directly rather than through purchase of various foods.

The company must decide the positive unit prices: y1,y2,…,ymy_1, y_2, \ldots, y_m for the nutrients so as to maximize revenue while at the same time being competitive with real food.
The cost of a unit food ii made synthetically from pure nutrients bought from the druggist must be no greater than cic_i, the market price of the food.
Thus, denoting by 𝐚i\bm{a}_i the ithi^{\text{th}} food, the company must satisfy 𝐲⊤𝐚i≤𝐜i\bm{y}^\top \bm{a}_i \leq \bm{c}_i for each ii.
Since bjb_j units of the jthj^{\text{th}} nutrient will be purchased, the problem of the druggist is on the right.





 
 
 
 
maximize𝐲⊤𝐛subject to𝐲⊤𝐀≤𝐜⊤,𝐲≥𝟎
\begin{align}
\operatorname{maximize} & \bm{y}^\top \bm{b} \\
\text{subject to} & \bm{y}^\top\bm{A} \leq \bm{c}^\top, \quad \bm{y} \geq \bm{0}
\end{align}
